title: nicole_malice
body:
"[i]Strong, beautiful, and invincible necromancer! Her servant is super strong too! She could beat up Misty any time if she really wanted to!![/i]"
 -Nicole Malice's in-game description.

"[i]Nicole Malice has polished up her necromancy skills, gotten a new eyeball servant and hat, and is all ready to kick [[Misty Hollow]]'s butt![/i]"
 -Skull's in-game description.

"[i]Nicole Malice obtained a new servant thanks to her sister, [[Persenachia]]. Misty still doesn't pay her much attention, but is secretly astonished at her growth.[/i]"
 -Knight's in-game description.

"[i]Perphaps an imitation of [[Persenachia]], Nicole has contracted with "Yomi", an ART-type servant. Apparently she had to travel quite some distance to obtain it.[/i]"
 -Yasha's in-game description.

A [[Mecha Musume]] from the game [[Cosmic Break]], Nicole Malice is a white-haired young necromancer who, judging by her descriptions, has a somewhat arrogant personality that diminishes as she grows. In-game, the original Malice can be obtained through the shop for 80000 UC or 80 RT while her red-haired variation, whose parts can't be changed, can be obtained through the Super UC Gara and her other variations are only obtainable through the RT Garapon system. 

Nicole Malice was [[Misty Hollow]]'s self-proclaimed rival ever since she started her career in the Cosmic Ark, although Misty supposedly never acknowledged Nicole as her equal during that time. While Nicole's descriptions directly mention Misty, none of Misty's descriptions mention her at all, however Knight's description states that Misty was astonished at her growth, while at the same time it doesn't make any antagonizing remarks at her on Nicole's part. This hints both at Malice's maturation and shows Misty's acknowledgement of her as an actual fighter.

During Nicole's early career as a Cosmic Hero, she relied on her first servant, Dead Eye, to deal significant damage to her opponents while absorbing their energy with her Soul Rod, a homing sub-weapon that replenishes the WB charge every hit. It can be assumed that Nicole met Misty during or even before the time when she became a newbie Hero since her first description already mentions Misty. 

After some time, Nicole realized she was still weaker than Misty and decided to learn more about necromancy, eventually summoning a better servant, Skull Eyes. Despite that, Misty was getting even stronger, and Nicole still considered herself too weak. This led her to call her sister, [[Persenachia]], to help her just as Misty acquired her VOID form. 

Nicole's plan backfired spectacularly, however, as Misty herself acknowledged Persenachia as a worthy rival. Even though Persenachia effectively stole Nicole's goal, she offered all her support to her little sister, helping her summon a new servant, Dead Phalanx. As Misty and Persenachia kept competing, Nicole began training swordsmanship with a weapon she forged herself, Soul Sword, and as soon as Misty made a contract with the lord of the underworld for more power, thus evolving once more into Raven, Malice resumed her career as Knight with an all-new fighting style, Dead Phalanx and a renewed confidence that, unbeknownst to her, finally earned Misty's respect.

Nicole's admiration for her older sister kept growing, what eventually led her into following Persenachia's steps and experimenting the ART-Type by making a contract with an ART servant, Yomi, also called Dead Slayer. Nicole apparently decided to use bladed weapons ever since she became Knight, as Yomi's "staff" is specifically a bladed staff, although most of the time she uses it to fire projectiles, sticking to her new ART-Type style.

title: lafiel_(cosmic_break)
body:
"[i]A high ranking knight who fights with time magic and a rapier. Once a low-born waif, her admiration for Sylvia's skill led her to join the Royal Guard where she serves as Vice Captain.[/i]

A [[mecha musume]] from the MMO [[Cosmic Break]], Lafiel is a serious, no-nonsense fencer who is a Vice Captain of the Royal Guard of Pritzl, answering only to the Captain herself, [[Sylvia (Cosmic Break)|]]. According to her, she used to be "a  bit of a troublemaker" who never lost a fight, but also didn't know how to avoid them. When she meet Sylvia on a random town, she immediately challenged the knight to a duel, was easily beat and subsequently sworn loyalty to her.

Her gameplay is built around precise hits, dodging and hit-and-run tactics. Her rapier's combo ends with a lunge towards the enemy's general direction, which can be used both for blowing them away and evading retaliation. Should the player stop her combo before the lunge, Lafiel will immediately do a backstep, which can be followed by a another lunge. The backstep will most likely dodge any physical counter-attack, but may become a liability agaisnt ranged enemies, so the player must carefully choose their opponents in order to use her full potential. Her rapier also has a Guard command which completely deflects attacks while active, useful for approaching an aware ranged enemy.

Aside from her rapier, Lafiel also carries a dagger which can be thrown at opponents, although its effectiveness is debatable, or used in a parry lunge which also inflicts a debuff on the enemy, causing 5% of their HP in damage should their Wonder Bit be activated. Said debuff is caused by any of her attacks when her Wonder Bit is activated.

Lafiel is near useless amidst a crowd of enemies due to the nature of her attacks. However, if mastered, she truly shines agaisnt small numbers of enemies.

title: sanshin
body:
The sanshin (ä¸‰ç·š, literally "three strings") is an Okinawan musical instrument and precursor of the Japanese shamisen. Often likened to a banjo, it consists of a snakeskin-covered body, neck and three strings.

Its close resemblance in both appearance and name to the Chinese sanxian suggests its Chinese origins, the old RyÅ«kyÅ« Kingdom (pre-Japanese Okinawa) having very close ties with China. In the 16th century, the sanshin reached the Japanese trading port at Sakai in Osaka, Japan. In mainland Japan, it evolved into the larger shamisen.

In mainland Japan, many people refer to the sanshin as jabisen (è›‡çš®ç·š, literally "snake-skin strings") or jamisen (è›‡ä¸‰ç·š, "snake three strings") because the body of the instrument has a snakeskin covering. Traditionally, it was covered with the skin of the Burmese python, but today, due to CITES regulations, the skin of the python reticulatus is also used, as well as cloth. A bamboo bridge raises the strings off the skin.

The Sanshin is played either with the traditional plectrum, made of horn and worn on the finger, the nail of the index finger, or, more recently, a guitar pick. 

Directly after WW2, with a scarcity of materials, Sanshin were made with flat tin cans and scrap wood, called Kankara Sanshin (ã‹ã‚“ã‹ã‚‰ ä¸‰ç·šï¼‰. These are still produced today, either as inexpensive instruments or, more often, souvenirs.

title: hild_(aa_megami-sama)
body:
Hild is an [[Aa Megami-sama]] character. She's the ruler of demons, holding the title of Daimakaicho (lit. Great Demon Leader) and is the opposite of Tyr, the leader of Heavens (also referred to as Almighty for most of the series). Still, she's [[Urd (Aa Megami-sama)|]]'s mother, whom she loves, even though the latter tries to keep a distance, fearing that getting too close to her would make her demon side take over. 

Despite being Tyr's first wife (or lover), Hild seems to get along with [[Belldandy]] and [[Skuld (Aa Megami-sama)|]], who remind her of their father, even though at some point in the series she antagonized them for a while, using a 1/1000th avatar of hers that she left behind after her visit to the mortal realm. 

It should be noted though that she probably held back considerably, since she's one of the most powerful entities in Aa Megami-sama, with the closest match being Tyr himself, or [[Ansuz]] (the mother of Belldandy and Skuld). Actually, her relationship with Ansuz strongly resembles the antagonistic attitude between Urd and Mara, even though their antics seem much more extreme and destructive. 

She's voiced by "Gara Takashima":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gara_Takashima].

She didn't want to release the winners, but Adel's sportsmanship told her to release them, since they won fair and square.
 
The next tournament, she joins Adel in his search for strong fighters and once again the hosts of the XI tournament. She eventually stops his battles just to speak with her brother or taunt his enemy. title: zero_(kof)
body:
Final boss of [[The King of Fighters 2000]]. Infamous for the "Zero Fart" move, which he kneels down creating a purple energy flow, turns his back and his cape gets blown upward as if he were farting.

During The King of Fighters '99, he was commanded to watch over the performance of the [[Kusanagi Kyou|Kusanagi]] cloning process, set forth by one of their lower ranked officers, [[Krizalid]]. Acting as the project supervisor, he monitored all actions done by Krizalid and also analyzed the performance of [[K' (kof)|]]. After he neutralizes the Kyo clones and terminates Krizalid, he begins to secretly build his own weapon from NESTS's technology called the "Zero Cannon", setting it to operate with the same technology found in Krizalid's battle armor.
 
He sets his plans into motion in KOF 2000. There, he impersonates Ling, a military commander and close friend to Heidern. Using his Ling persona as a decoy, he tricks and captures Heidern to stop the military resistance against him. He then fights the winning team of the tournament, planning to use their fighting capacities to power his Zero Cannon. His plans were foiled by [[Kula Diamond]], [[Foxy (KOF)|Foxy]], [[Diana (KoF)|Diana]] and [[Candy Diamond]]. The game's story highly implies that he is killed by [[Whip (KoF)|Whip]] after he privately reveals some shocking information to her.

It was later revealed that this Zero is a clone of the original [[Original Zero|Zero]].

He fights using a bladed cape as a weapon, as well as using shadow manipulation to trap enemies.

Voiced by Futogane Kinta.

body:
Armor made from small metal rings linked together into a mesh.  Also known as simply "mail" or "maille."

European garments made with mail are leggings (chausses), mail hoods (coif) and mail mittens (mitons). A mail collar hanging from a helmet is camail or aventail. A mail collar worn strapped around the neck was called a pixane or standard. A shirt made from mail is a hauberk if knee-length and a haubergeon if mid-thigh length.

Japanese chainmail is called [i]kusari[/i] (é–, lit. "chain") and was used extensively alongside the more distinctive and better known lamellar armors.

Raglan sleeves are sleeves attached to a garment via a diagonal seam from the armpit to the neckline (rather than a simple circular seam at the edge of the shoulder). They are often made in a different color than the torso of the garment and are constructed from one piece of material. Raglan sleeves are commonly used in sportswear, as they are designed to give greater freedom of movement for the arm and shoulder. 

T-shirts with this type of sleeve are sometimes called "baseball shirts" due to their popularity of use as undershirts for baseball uniforms. Raglan sleeves became very popular in fashion outside of sports in the start of the 1970's.

title: kyurem
body:
[[Pokemon]] #646 in the National PokÃ©Dex, a dual-type Dragon/Ice Legendary PokÃ©mon.

While it is not known to evolve into or from any PokÃ©mon, it has two other formes, which are activated by using the DNA Splicers on it and either [[Reshiram]] or [[Zekrom]], resulting in a process called Absofusion that removes Reshiram or Zekrom from the party until the fusion is undone. It will then become [[White Kyurem]] (with Reshiram) or [[Black Kyurem]] (with Zekrom).

Along with [[Reshiram]] and [[Zekrom]], Kyurem is a member of the Tao trio, which exists in the legends of the Unova region.

As both Black Kyurem and White Kyurem, it is the game mascot of PokÃ©mon Black 2 and White 2, respectively. 

Kyurem is a gray and blue, bipedal PokÃ©mon of indefinable but seemingly draconic basis. Kyurem has a blue head and snout and has yellow eyes without pupils, has a pair of pointed light bluish horns on its head and a yellow crest on its skull. Three pointed teeth jut out the bottom of either side of its jaws, which are frozen shut by the ice covering its head. Its long, gray neck has lines running around its whole body, legs, arms and tail. It has two arms, each with its own claw and each arm is jointed together from its oddly shaped blue wings, which are believed to be used for flying and storing cold air. Each wing has two spikes of ice. The ice covering the wings can break, revealing gray tendril-like appendages on Kyurem's back. The right side of its body seems to be damaged in some way, as the wing and horn on its head on that side are shorter; the right side of its head also has a spiked edge near its jaw hinge that is absent from its left. Its legs are somewhat slender, and has three sharp ice-like claws on each enormous foot. Its tail has three blue conical spikes on its tip, and appears to be some sort of propulsion device or a container of energy.

Next PokÃ©mon: [[Keldeo]]

title: crimrose
body:
"[i]A female robot from an outer dimension. 50% of her body consist of Zias geo-cells, allowing her to move with grace and precision.[/i]"

A [[mecha musume]] from the game [[Cosmic Break]], Crimrose is shown to be a cheerful and carefree girl. As a robot, she is characterized by her long hair, peculiar feet, and her armor (more specifically her upper armor that barely cover any part of her chest).

She is the basic air unit players can get at the start of the game, and also has a [[chibi]] form. There are several variations of her hair color and parts in-game.

Crimrose is one of the few characters in [[Cosmic Break]] that currently have an alternate/'promotion' form, along with [[Lily Rain]], [[Winberrl]] and [[LazFlamme]]. Her alternate form is known as [[Seraph Crimrose]], characterized by a pair of additional wings protruding from her back.

She is pretty much considered the [[Cosmic Break]] mascot and one of the main characters of the Cosmic Break story. She is also featured as an NPC in the game.

While her story is still unclear, it is said in the mangas that she met [[Ivis]] in a research facility when they were younger, and died during experiments to find a host for a powerful weapon, along with several other children. Her death made Ivis go berserk, sucessfully activating the weapon and killing everyone in the facility. Crimrose was later revived at the Cosmic Ark without any memories of her time alive and met Ivis again, although the latter had developed an obssession for Crimrose because of the traumas she experienced in the research facility and, after learning that Crimrose didn't remember her and seeing her acting friendly towards other people, went berserk once again. Her rampage was stopped by Seraph Crimrose, fortunately before she killed anyone, and she escaped. It is stated in Ivis' in-game description that Crimrose bought her back to her senses, although this is never shown. 

Crimrose is later seen along with Ivis in Ground Area, talking to player about their ACs, and as a normal student in Angel Academy.

In the game [[Cosmic Break 2]], another Crimrose from the alternate timeline is one of the starter characters.

When the image resolution on Danbooru differs from the image resolution at the source. The following two tags can be used with this tag.

* [[source_larger]]:

Because of the upbringing by her household she has rarely a chance to meet or interact with others that she could open her heart to, thus has a hard time showing her true feelings but deep down is a very expressive and [[tsundere]] young girl. Despite living under strict parents that banned all things anime and game related she still developed a love for them and secretly works toward her dream of becoming a voice actor. 

Her appearance is that of a [[blunt_bangs|blunt bang]] [[silver_hair|silvered]] prim and proper "Ojou-sama":https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/Ojou with [[long_hair|long flowing hair]], giving off a very cool and elegant vibe but those that get close to her will see that she can be quite silly at times, especially during her "Rena teatime" when she interact and holds conversation with her chat regarding the weather, her day or how she is still sleepy right after having just gotten out of bed to stream. She wears a [[layered_dress|multi-layered]] [[long_sleeves|long sleeve]] [[white_dress|frilly white dress]] adorned in [[black_ribbon|ribbons]] and a [[brooch]] with a [[black_bow|black bow]]. Her eyes are [[blue_eyes|light blue-ish purple]] and she sports a slightly stoic yet sleepy look with jeweled [[earrings]] hidden behind on her ears.  

Rena understands English well enough to read and speak it, as well as understands German that she notes she's been studying. She enjoys fantasy and tea, as well as chocolate and other confectionery. As a "Vseiyuu", whenever she plays a game she would also tend to read out in-game texts in different ranges of voices based on what she think the character sounds like. She is friends with her fellow Voice-Ore members, [[Himukai_Kogane|Himukai Kogane]] and [[Aoi_Mizuki|Aoi Mizuki]], who often drop by in her chat and refer to them as Koga-chan and Mizuki-chan.

Her other emoji is also ğŸ•Š, a white bird/Dove based on her name "Shiratori ([b]ç™½é³¥[/b])" which reads as such respectively (white bird), and her personal greeting to her fans is [i]Guten Rena[/i] based on the German phrase of "Good morning/day ([i]Guten Tag/Morgen[/i]) and [i]TschÃ¼ss[/i] ("Good bye/Bye Bye" in German). title: ever_given_(evergreen)
body:
The [i]Ever Given[/i] is a Golden-class container ship built by the Japanese Imabari Shipbuilding company and operated by the Taiwanese [[Evergreen Marine Corporation]].  She initially had a theoretical carrying capacity of 20,338 Twenty-foot Equivalent Units (TEU), the rough volume of 20,388 standard 20-foot long shipping containers.  After receiving a retrofit to add scrubbers to reduce emissions her theoretical carrying capacity was reduced to 20,124 TEU.

In February 2019, while on route from Hamburg, Germany to Rotterdam, Netherlands the [i]Ever Given[/i] collided and severely damaged the docked Hamburg ferry [i]Finkenwerder[/i].  This may have happened due to high winds at the time.

In March 2021, while traveling through the Suez Canal the [i]Ever Given[/i] was caught up in a sand storm and ran aground blocking the canal. It was finally freed from the canal after six days.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia - Ever Given":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ever_Given]

A "Heian era":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heian_period historical figure, approximately of the 11th or 12th century, Myouren was a Buddhist monk born in Shinano Province, or Nagano Prefecture, as it's known today. 

He trained at the Chougosonshi Temple (æœè­·å­«å­å¯º) on Mount Shigi (ä¿¡è²´å±±) near Nara, which he established. His most significant role is in the "[i]Shigisan-engi[/i]":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shigisan-engi emaki. 

The [i]Shigisan-engi[/i] is also the basis for [[Touhou|Touhou's]] [i][[Undefined Fantastic Object]][/i]. In it, it is told that he had an older sister, who was worried about him. So she searched for Myouren and after being reunited with him, the two lived together again. This woman is the basis for [[Hijiri Byakuren]], whose brother's later death drove her to despair and made her fear her own mortality.

His role in Touhou is minor, only serving as backstory for Byakuren. However, ZUN has said he once considered Myouren for a main role in UFO, albeit as an old man. No official character design exists for him, leaving his appearance up to speculation. Fanart typically depicts him with [[gradient hair]] like his sister's, despite the fact that a Buddhist monk would normally have [[bald|shaved off all his hair]].

title: kirby_mass_attack
body:
[[Kirby (series)|]] game.

Ever wanted to control 10 Kirbies at once? No? Well, too bad! [[Necrodeus]] is having none of [[Kirby]] being alive, so he decides to split the puffball into 10 smaller ones so that he has an easier time picking them off. One manages to escape the carnage and decides to save Dream Land from this new crisis!

Also joining him are the returning Squeaks, with [[Daroach]] at the helm once more. This time, he gives hints and advice to help Kirby in his quest.

Like [[Kirby Canvas Curse]], this game is entirely controlled with a touch screen in order to navigate all 10 of Kirby to safety. You don't have [[copy_ability|copy abilities]] this time around, so be careful!
